While states involving 1p-1 h core excitations can be well accounted for by large scale shell model calculations [59], more collective (phonon-type) core excitations require alternative approaches [125–127]. In such a heavy-mass region, phonons cannot be fully treated by the shell model, as it would require full calculations in a configuration space that encompasses proton and neutron orbitals below and above 132\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{132}$$\end{document}Sn. For this purpose, a new microscopic and self-consistent model (named “Hybrid Configuration Mixing” (HCM)) has been developed, with the aim of describing states with different degrees of collectivity [55, 128, 129]. The HCM model has no free parameters and is self-consistent in the sense that both single-particle states and phonons come out of Hartree-Fock (HF) and Random Phase Approximation (RPA) calculations performed with the Skyrme SkX interaction [130]. In the case of 133\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{133}$$\end{document}Sb and 131\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$^{131}$$\end{document}Sn [55, 131], the model is found to reproduce well the energy sequence of the high-spin states observed experimentally, pointing to a fast evolution of the wave function composition, from collective to non-collective character, with increasing spin. In the case of 133\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
