In even–even nuclei, the signature of octupole deformation is the presence of interleaved positive- and negative-parity levels forming a single rotational band, with opposite parity levels connected by large electric octupole (E3) matrix elements and decaying by fast electric dipole (E1) transitions. In odd-mass nuclei, the octupole deformation signature is the appearance of parity doublets, i.e., pair of states with the same spin, opposite parities and large E3 matrix elements between them. Much faster E1 rates are expected for members of the parity doublet as compared to neighboring systems without octupole deformation (see Fig. 33). Moreover, from the study of the band structure in terms of B(E1)/B(E2) branching ratios associated to the out-of-band/in-band decay, and from the knowledge of the electric quadrupole moment Q0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Q_0$$\end{document}, the intrinsic electric dipole moment D0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_0$$\end{document} can be deducted, assuming the rotational formula D0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$_0$$\end{document} = 5/16B(E1)/B(E2)×Q0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sqrt{5/16 B(E1)/B(E2)} \times Q_0$$\end{document}. Its size (of the order of 0.1 and 0.3 efm in the Ba and Ra region, respectively) is an important indication of the magnitude of the octupole correlations, whose nature (static or dynamical) can be inferred from the plot of the ratio of the rotational frequency of the parity doublets, ω(π=-1)/ω(π=+1)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
